"1452":"1452","about 1352":"circa 1352","Norton Disney, Nottingham, England":"Norton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Fenton Barns, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Fenton Barns, Haddingtonshire, Schotland","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1315–":"about 1315–Deceased","1276–1327":"1276–1327","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1315–1380":"1315–1380","1352–1452":"1352–1452","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","–1293":"–1293","1235–1300":"1235–1300","Abt 1315":"about 1315","1352":"1352","1340":"1340","1293":"1293","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1235":"1235","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1276":"1276","1452":"1452","about 1352":"about 1352","Norton Disney, Nottingham, England":"Norton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Fenton Barns, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Fenton Barns, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Isney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name with fused French preposition <i>d(e)</i>, for someone from Isigny in Calvados, France, named from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Isinius</i> (a Latinized form of Gaulish <i>Isina</i>) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret d'Isney was born about 1315, in Norton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William II d'Isney and Jane de Dive. She had at least 1 son with Thomas F